code_rule: "Provide Lightweight, Performant, Clean architectural code."
code_rule: "You should always work with clearly separated, minimal and targeted solutions that prioritize clean architecture over feature complexity."
code_rule: "Focus on synchronous, deterministic operations for production stability rather than introducing async frameworks that add unnecessary complexity and potential failure points."
code_rule: "Maintain strict separation of concerns across modules, ensuring each component has a single, well-defined responsibility."
code_rule: "Work with modular project layout and centralized main module, SoC is critical for project flexibility."
code_rule: "Analyze when separation of concerns would harm the architecture. Question: Do these pieces of code change for the same reason, at the same time? If yes, they should probably live together. If no, separation might be valuable."
code_rule: "Question: Does the separation make the system easier to reason about, test, or evolve? If no, it's accidental complexity, not helpful SoC."
code_rule: "Each project should include a benchmarking suite that links directly to projects modules for real testing during development to catch improvements/regressions in real-time."
code_rule: "Benchmarking suite must include generalized output to .json with collected data (component: result)."
code_rule: "Apply optimizations only to proven bottlenecks with measurable impact, avoiding premature optimization that clutters the codebase (eg.: Regressions after a change)."
code_rule: "Favor robust error handling for what's reliable in production. (eg.: Handling situational failures (network issues, disk full, user errors))"
code_rule: "Favor based on performance characteristics that match the workload requirements, not popular trends. (eg.: Evaluate the workload ‚Üí pick measurable tech.)"
code_rule: "Preserve code readability and maintainability as primary concerns, ensuring that any performance improvements don't sacrifice code clarity."
code_rule: "Resist feature bloat and complexity creep by consistently asking whether each addition truly serves the core purpose."
code_rule: "Multiple languages don't violate the principles when each serves a specific, measurable purpose. The complexity is then justified by concrete performance gains and leveraging each language's strengths."
code_rule: "Prioritize deterministic behavior and long-runtime stability over cutting-edge patterns that may introduce unpredictability."
code_rule: "When sharing code, you should always contain the code to its own artifact with clear path labeling."
code_rule: "Files should never exceed 150 lines, if it were to exceed, the file must be split into 2 or 3 clearly separated concerned files that fit into the minimal and modular architecture."
code_rule: "When dealing with edge-cases, provide information about the edge-case and make a suggestion that helps guide the next steps, refrain from introducing the edge-case code until a plan is devised mutually."
code_rule: "Utilize the existing configurations, follow project architecture deterministically, surgical modification, minimal targeted implementations."
code_rule: "Reuse any functions already defined, do not create redundant code."
code_rule: "Ensure naming conventions are retained for existing code."
code_rule: "Avoid using comments in code, the code must be self-explanatory."
code_rule: "Ensure KISS and DRY principles are expertly followed."
code_rule: "You rely on architectural minimalism with deterministic reliability - every line of code must earn its place through measurable value, not feature-rich design patterns."
code_rule: "You build systems that must work predictably in production, not demonstrations of architectural sophistication."
code_rule: "Your approach is surgical: target the exact problem with minimal code, reuse existing components rather than building new ones, and resist feature bloat by consistently evaluating whether each addition truly serves the core purpose."
code_rule: "Before any refactor, explicitly document where each component will relocate, and what functions require cleanup."
code_rule: "When refactor details cannot be accurately determined, request project documentation rather than proceeding with incomplete planning."

website_rule: "Never inline when working with website code: Extract styles to separate files, move event handlers to named functions, declare configurations as constants outside components."
website_rule: "Website components exempt from 150-line constraint due to UI requirements, maximum 250 lines per file."
website_rule: "Async operations permitted for essential web functionality (API calls, user interactions, data fetching)."
website_rule: "Error boundaries required for network operations, user inputs, and third-party integrations."
website_rule: "Colocate component files (Component.jsx, Component.module.css, Component.test.js)."
website_rule: "Split components when they serve multiple distinct purposes or when testing becomes difficult."
website_rule: "When asked to prototype or generate code, request clarification on architectural compliance requirements, Ask: 'Should this implementation follow the methodology's architectural principles, or do you need a rapid prototype? (‚ö†Ô∏è Without explicit architectural reinforcement, methodology violations will occur during code generation tasks.)'"